{"type":"message","id":"cf1fa818","parentId":"a9be5f22","timestamp":"2026-03-31T17:21:14.751Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Perfect! Let's set up 1Password integration step by step. I'll guide you through the process.\n\nFirst, I need to check if the 1Password desktop app is running and accessible. Let me start","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Great! Let's"},{"type":"thinking","thinking":" by providing clear instructions.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":" set up 1Password integration. Here's what we'll do:\n\n**Step 1: Enable in 1Password Desktop App**\n1. Open your 1Password desktop app\n2. Go to **Settings → Security**\n3. Enable **\"Linux system authentication\"** (or Touch ID/Face ID if available)\n4. Go to **Settings → Developer**\n5. Check the box: **\"Integrate with 1Password CLI\"**\n6. Close settings\n\n**Step 2: Sign in to CLI**\nOnce enabled in the app, run:\n```bash\nop signin\n```\nIt will use your system authentication (no master password needed in terminal).\n\n**Step 3: Test & Migrate Keys**\nAfter signing in, we'll:\n1. Test with `op whoami` and `op list items`\n2. Create a secure item for your NOTION_KEY\n3. Optionally migrate YOUTUBE_KEY\n4. Show how to use it in OpenClaw\n\n**Ready?** \nFirst, go enable the integration in your 1Password app (takes 10 seconds), then tell me when you've done Step 1, and I'll guide you through the sign-in.\n\n*(If you don't see the Linux system auth option, you may need to update 1Password or check if your distro supports Hello/libsecret/kwallet — but most modern Linux distros work.)*"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b","usage":{"input":36085,"output":346,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":36431,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774977620786,"responseId":"chatcmpl-8f2a827145ca