{"type":"message","id":"ec1d5b8e","parentId":"47aa91b9","timestamp":"2026-03-31T19:18:10.407Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_0d67a5ea20484ae78ff1393a","toolName":"process","content":[{"type":"text","text":"cher sub-agents model.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 5,\n        \"cited_text\": \"Now it has other agents that we ask, do you have the API key? No, it won't. We need to set it up. So, the reason I can stop by, okay, tell me the best way to and secure way to give you API keys. So I will show you the secure way to give API keys and I want you to realize this is the keys that I'm using if by any chance if I don't blur it the chances are I will hook the key as soon as the video is done. So set locally this is practical and most safe right and the way we do that is we need to first export\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 6,\n        \"cited_text\": \"it in our terminal and so for example i want to give it anthropic key okay and where is my anthropic key i can go to let's say we want to give the anthropic api key and what would i do to give this an anthropic api key is i will just. Do an export anthropic api key something like this in my terminal and then i need to restart the gateway and say hey right now open a cloud key anthropic api key is available as an environment variable i want you to use that and choose that for subagent and open law is the key to work with i will show what i\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 7,\n        \"cited_text\": \"and then he switches to kimike 2.5 to nvidia street tier for daily operations and then a high Q for heartbeat less than a dollar a month and DC for coding tests. He will use Whisper for voice transcription. His total monthly cost is about $60 and that includes 11 labs for voice loads and a dedicated phone number for signal. And this is the entire breakdown that he's done. That's a fully autonomous agent around 24-7 for $60. And notice the pattern. it's exactly what we covered you know expensive model\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n\n\nProcess exited with code 0."}],"details":{"status":"completed","sessionId":"wild-sage","exitCode":0,"aggregated":"{\n  \"value\": {\n    \"answer\": \"Step 2 of the OpenClaw setup guide is **Sub-agent Configuration** [1]. This step focuses on setting up a **\\\"main brain\\\" model** to work alongside cheaper **\\\"muscle agents\\\"** so they function as a cohesive team [1], [2]. \\n\\nThe sources emphasize that this is a critical stage because OpenClaw frequently **breaks** if the configuration is handled incorrectly, such as by asking the agent to change its own settings [1], [3]. To implement this successfully, you should use a **specific prompt** to define agent guidelines and manually export **API keys** (like those for Anthropic or Google Cloud) as environment variables in your terminal [4], [5], [6]. This dual-model architecture allows you to use powerful, expensive models for orchestration while utilizing \\\"muscle\\\" models (like Gemini Flash or Haiku) for daily operations to **save tokens** and stay under budget [2], [7].\",\n    \"conversation_id\": \"e6888339-841f-428d-97fb-433fce5cb165\",\n    \"sources_used\": [\n      \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\"\n    ],\n    \"citations\": {\n      \"1\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"2\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"3\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"4\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"5\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"6\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"7\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\"\n    },\n    \"references\": [\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 1,\n        \"cited_text\": \"laid it out so you can jump to any section. You don't have to watch this in order. So we have about 23 chapters covered in this course. Let's take a quick look. Chapter one is installation and setup. This is the fastest setup you'll find, plus how to get up to $1,500 in free API credits across AWS, Google Cloud, and Azure OpenAI. Chapter 2, sub-agent configuration. How to set up your main brain model and cheaper muzzle agents so they work together without breaking your configuration. Trust me, open clock breaks when you do this wrong. I'll show you the right way.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 2,\n        \"cited_text\": \"minimax or a kimiki 2.5 these can be your muscle agents who can do the work right so this setup has helped me tremendously when i was starting out and i was hitting limits with my even with my cloud max 200 plan i was hitting in limits so i started doing opus as a control and all the agents as the muscle so that is only one but we have eight more eight layer token optimization stack now these are the things that i found out after researching a lot of videos i looked at some of the well-performing videos of there are a lot of people who've done\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 3,\n        \"cited_text\": \"if you don't watch this video, you will miss this part, which is really, really important. Open Claw has a habit of breaking when you ask it to make config changes. So, I'm not sure if you face this. Anytime I ask it to, oh, can you add this sub-agent? Can you add this model? I really love Alex Finn's content, but his best advice is, oh, ask your OpenFlow agent, it will know what to do, tell your OpenFlow agent, do this, it will do that. Maybe his Opus 4.6 did, but even I used Opus 4.6 for a while now,\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 4,\n        \"cited_text\": \"define agent and agent are less minimal config only so what you would do is you will copy the whole thing you will copy the prompt and don't ask OpenClaw to figure it out. Wherever you have your OpenClaw agent you go to your agent and say. I want you to create a sub-agent and this is the guideline. And you paste the entire prompt that is left. This is the guideline, step one. And it will give this output. I set this up for you. Applied config changes, researcher kept research at minimum. Then added model, sober write, researcher sub-agents model.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 5,\n        \"cited_text\": \"Now it has other agents that we ask, do you have the API key? No, it won't. We need to set it up. So, the reason I can stop by, okay, tell me the best way to and secure way to give you API keys. So I will show you the secure way to give API keys and I want you to realize this is the keys that I'm using if by any chance if I don't blur it the chances are I will hook the key as soon as the video is done. So set locally this is practical and most safe right and the way we do that is we need to first export\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 6,\n        \"cited_text\": \"it in our terminal and so for example i want to give it anthropic key okay and where is my anthropic key i can go to let's say we want to give the anthropic api key and what would i do to give this an anthropic api key is i will just. Do an export anthropic api key something like this in my terminal and then i need to restart the gateway and say hey right now open a cloud key anthropic api key is available as an environment variable i want you to use that and choose that for subagent and open law is the key to work with i will show what i\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 7,\n        \"cited_text\": \"and then he switches to kimike 2.5 to nvidia street tier for daily operations and then a high Q for heartbeat less than a dollar a month and DC for coding tests. He will use Whisper for voice transcription. His total monthly cost is about $60 and that includes 11 labs for voice loads and a dedicated phone number for signal. And this is the entire breakdown that he's done. That's a fully autonomous agent around 24-7 for $60. And notice the pattern. it's exactly what we covered you know expensive model\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n","name":"nlm notebook"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774984690401}}
