{"type":"message","id":"70c48a71","parentId":"81a75b96","timestamp":"2026-03-31T19:18:34.183Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_526ac48429b847d9a0ef9a51","toolName":"process","content":[{"type":"text","text":"        \"citation_number\": 5,\n        \"cited_text\": \"minimax or a kimiki 2.5 these can be your muscle agents who can do the work right so this setup has helped me tremendously when i was starting out and i was hitting limits with my even with my cloud max 200 plan i was hitting in limits so i started doing opus as a control and all the agents as the muscle so that is only one but we have eight more eight layer token optimization stack now these are the things that i found out after researching a lot of videos i looked at some of the well-performing videos of there are a lot of people who've done\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 6,\n        \"cited_text\": \"parts that are reloading 90 percent of the cost it's really great people are missing it. Even if you have a model that is not as expensive, you should still do this because even if you take Kimi K 2.5 API price in. And this is the final one. We have sub-agent isolation. What is this? Multi-agent coordination is expensive. It is almost 3.5x more tokens than single agent setups. And what is the fix for that? Fix is you isolate subtasks with forward slash spawn. So each agent runs in clean context. So instead of asking your main agent to do everything, If you look at the example\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 7,\n        \"cited_text\": \"that we were doing earlier, I was asking it to use Claude Sonnet to create an article for us. You can do that for various reasons. You can do that because Sonnet is good for certain tasks. But the idea is you spawn a researcher and you assign a task. So the spawn agent gets a clean context from, you know, your main agent's context stays lean. So this is critical for three roles architecture your architect stays lightweight managers coordinate and workers execute in isolation each role gets only the context it needs not the\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n\n\nProcess exited with code 0."}],"details":{"status":"completed","sessionId":"faint-nexus","exitCode":0,"aggregated":"{\n  \"value\": {\n    \"answer\": \"Step 2 of the OpenClaw setup covers **Sub-agent Configuration** [1]. This stage focuses on setting up a **\\\"main brain\\\" model** to work alongside **cheaper \\\"muscle agents\\\"** so they can function as a cohesive team [1], [2].\\n\\nThe core elements of this step include:\\n\\n*   **Preventing Configuration Errors:** This is a critical phase because OpenClaw frequently **breaks** if the configuration is handled incorrectly, particularly if you ask the agent to change its own settings [1], [3].\\n*   **Structured Setup:** To avoid errors, the guide recommends using a **specific prompt** to define agent guidelines rather than letting the AI attempt to figure out the configuration itself [4].\\n*   **Token Efficiency:** By coordinating a high-performance \\\"brain\\\" model (like Claude Opus) with \\\"muscle\\\" models (like Gemini Flash or Haiku), you can significantly **reduce costs** while maintaining high-quality output [2], [5].\\n*   **Isolation and Spawning:** It introduces the practice of **isolating subtasks** using the `forward slash spawn` command [6]. This ensures that each sub-agent runs in a **clean context**, preventing \\\"context window bloat\\\" and ensuring the \\\"architect\\\" model stays lightweight [6], [7].\\n*   **Three-Role Framework:** This configuration follows an architecture where the **architect** stays lightweight, **managers** coordinate, and **workers** (sub-agents) execute specialized tasks in isolation [7].\",\n    \"conversation_id\": \"e6888339-841f-428d-97fb-433fce5cb165\",\n    \"sources_used\": [\n      \