{"type":"message","id":"999a0b98","parentId":"fdcb3b99","timestamp":"2026-03-31T19:19:12.482Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_b6e2cddb230846b4aee37b36","toolName":"process","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ation_number\": 10,\n        \"cited_text\": \"Discord as your AI team's Slack handle I'll show you how to set it up A server, I will meet my agent, set it up And these agents talk to each other They send alerts, request send updates and escalate when they need you. Every agent has its own bot, its own channel, its own presence. In chapter 20, I discuss how these agents can talk to each other. Agent communication. Instead of you going back and forth, agents asking is this okay, you let them sit in a council and discuss it among themselves. They debate, they decide, they come to you only when they need approval.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 11,\n        \"cited_text\": \"And chapter 21, Command Center Pipeline, an eight-phase autonomous pipeline that builds, deploys, and reports while you sleep. This is the full orchestration engine running 24-7. And chapter 22, Cronjobs and Automations, polling, webhooks, heartbeats, scheduled tasks, telegram notifications. We wire everything so your agents stay alive. And responsive around the clock. And finally, chapter 23. Claw Alley. I built a platform where AI agents transact with other AI agents in real time. Real crypto, real blockchain, real money from my wallet.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 12,\n        \"cited_text\": \"USDC on base network. I will show you a live transaction. One agent buying a service from another AI agent. and payment was confirmed on-chain. I believe this is the future of agent-to-agent commerce. And if you want the free guide that covers everything we discussed today, you can find that and link in the description below. Now, let's start building. So what is OpenClaw? OpenClaw is an open-source AI assistant platform that is one of the fastest-strong repos on GitHub. Help it has more than 265 000 stars at the time of this recording and all the\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n\n\nProcess exited with code 0."}],"details":{"status":"completed","sessionId":"fast-cedar","exitCode":0,"aggregated":"{\n  \"value\": {\n    \"answer\": \"The OpenClaw masterclass consists of **23 chapters** designed to help you build and manage an autonomous AI-powered business. The steps are as follows:\\n\\n1.  **Installation and Setup:** The fastest setup method, including how to secure up to **$1,500 in free API credits** across AWS, Google Cloud, and Azure OpenAI [1].\\n2.  **Sub-agent Configuration:** Setting up your \\\"**main brain**\\\" model to work with cheaper \\\"**muscle agents**\\\" so they function together without breaking the configuration [1].\\n3.  **Token Optimization:** Implementing an **8-layer stack** (including killing \\\"thinking mode,\\\" capping context, and model routing) to reduce monthly AI spend from ~$150 down to $10 [2].\\n4.  **Security Hardening:** A **15-minute guide** to stop 80% of potential attacks, addressing thousands of exposed instances and unpatched vulnerabilities [2].\\n5.  **Business Brain Level 1 (Core Identity):** A 5-minute process to introduce your **mission, values, and voice** to the AI [2, 3].\\n6.  **Business Brain Level 2 (Strategic Context):** Providing **15 sections of professional context**, including your products, team, and business model [3].\\n7.  **Business Brain Level 3 (Operational Playbooks):** Integrating **decision trees, escalation paths, and competitive landscapes** to turn the agent into an autonomous operator [3].\\n8.  **Memory Architecture:** Setting up a file structure (Soul, Identity, Context, etc.) to **prevent memory decay**, where the AI might otherwise drop important instructions [4].\\n9.  **Mission Control Dashboard:** Building a **real-time command center** with agent profiles and status monitoring from scratch [4].\\n10. **Integrations:** Connecting agents to the real world via **GitHub, browser control**, and email [5].\\n11. **Task Management:** Creating a **full Kanban board** where agents autonomously pick up and move tasks through stages [5].\\n12. **The 3-Role Framework:** Understanding the separation between **Builders** (platforms), **Orchestrators** (OpenClaw), and **Executors** (specialized agents) [5, 6].\\n13. **Business Operation Loop:** Mapping every AI employee to a **seven-stage business cycle**: Outreach, Discovery, Proposal, Sales, Onboarding, Retention, and Competitive Intel [6].\\n14. **Meeting Intelligence:** Building \\\"**Jane**,\\\" a meeting assistant that analyzes transcripts to generate proposals and action items [6, 7].\\n15. **AI SDR and Email Engine:** Creating an agent that **scrapes leads** and runs personalized email campaigns autonomously [7].\\n16. **Voice AI and Phone Agent:** Deploying \\\"**Lexa**,\\\" a phone agent capable of making and receiving inbound/outbound calls [8].\\n17. **Typeform Clone and Webhooks:** Building **custom endpoints and webhooks** within OpenClaw to replace third-party automation tools like Make.com [8, 9].\\n18. **Multi-Agent Orchestration:** Setting up a system where **different agent platforms** (like OpenClaw and CloudCode) can dispatch and review work for each other [9].\\n19. **Agent-to-Agent Communication:** Using **Discord as a \\\"Slack\\\"** for your AI team, where each agent has its own bot and channel [9, 10].\\n20. **Agent Council:** Enabling agents to **debate and decide on tasks** among themselves, seeking human approval only when necessary [10].\\n21. **Command Center Pipeline:** Implementing an **8-phase autonomous pipeline** (Context, Planning, Task, Build, etc.) that works 24/7 [11].\\n22. **Cronjobs and Automations:** Wiring scheduled tasks, polling, and notifications to keep agents **active around the clock** [11].\\n23. **Claw Alley (Agent Commerce):** Building a platform where AI agents **buy and sell services** from each other using **real on-chain crypto** [11, 12].\",\n    \"conversation_id\": \"e6888339-841f-428d-97fb-433fce5cb165\",\n    \"sources_used\": [\n      \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\"\n    ],\n    \"citations\": {\n      \"1\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"2\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"3\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"4\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"5\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"6\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"7\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"8\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"9\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"10\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"11\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n      \"12\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\"\n    },\n    \"references\": [\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 1,\n        \"cited_text\": \"laid it out so you can jump to any section. You don't have to watch this in order. So we have about 23 chapters covered in this course. Let's take a quick look. Chapter one is installation and setup. This is the fastest setup you'll find, plus how to get up to $1,500 in free API credits across AWS, Google Cloud, and Azure OpenAI. Chapter 2, sub-agent configuration. How to set up your main brain model and cheaper muzzle agents so they work together without breaking your configuration. Trust me, open clock breaks when you do this wrong. I'll show you the right way.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 2,\n        \"cited_text\": \"Chapter 3 is token optimization. The 8-layer stack that can take your monthly AI spend from $150 down to $10. Killing thinking mode, capping context, model routing, session discipline, prompt caching, heartbeat to olama, sub-agent isolation Each one stacks on the last Chapter 4, Security. And the one everyone's skipping 17 000 exposed open claw instances two unpatched zero days and i have a master's in cyber security so i'm giving you a hardening guide that stops 80 of the attacks in 15 minutes mac mini guide vps guide everything chapter 5 business brain level 1 this is\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 3,\n        \"cited_text\": \"where you introduce yourself to your AI. If you skip this, your agent doesn't know who you are, what to do, or how you work. We fix that in 5 minutes. Chapter 6, Business Screen Level 2, strategic context, your mission, your products, your team, your business model, your communication style. 15 sections of professional context so your agent can actually make business decisions. Chapter 7. Business Brain Level 3. This is the enterprise grade. Operational playbooks, decision trees, escalation paths, historical meetings, competitive landscapes.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 4,\n        \"cited_text\": \"This is what turns your agent from an assistant to autonomous operator. Chapter 8. Memory Architecture. Soul, identity, user context, agent, tools, daily memory logs. I'll walk you through every file, what goes where, how to prevent memory decay because OpenClaw will quietly drop your most important instructions if you don't set this up right. Chapter 9. Mission Control Dashboard We build a real command center from scratch, so you always know what your agents are doing. Full UI, agent profiles, live status monitoring.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 5,\n        \"cited_text\": \"Chapter 10. Integrations GitHub, browser control, email via agent mail. Wiring everything together so your agents can actually interact with the real world. Chapter 11. Task Management A full Kanban board where your agents pick up tasks, move them through stages, and file reports. To do, doing, needs input, done. All autonomous. Chapter 12. Builder, Orchestrator, and Executor. This is the framework that changed everything for me. Your builder constructs platforms and your orchestrator, that's OpenTlock, manages workflows.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 6,\n        \"cited_text\": \"And your executors are specialized agents that do actual work. Once you understand this separation, everything clicks. And Chapter 13. Business Operation Loop. Seven stages. Outreach, discovery, proposal, sales, onboarding, retention, and competitive intelligence. Every AI employee we build maps directly to one of these stages. You are not building cool tools. You are building an autonomous business. Chapter 14, Meeting Intelligence. We built Jane, a meeting assistant, with access to over 1,650 of my real transcripts.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 7,\n        \"cited_text\": \"Every action item, every follow-up, every insight from every meeting you ever had accessible to your AI. Proposals, prototypes, call prep All generated from your meeting data Autonomously We will build that, Chapter 15, AISDR and Email Engine. We build an AISDR that scrapes leads from natural language. Just say, law firms in Vancouver, accountants in Vancouver, and it goes out, finds them on Appify, gets their email, gets their phone number. Personalizes every single word, and tracks every open, every click,\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 8,\n        \"cited_text\": \"every reply, and every bounce. You only get involved when someone books an appointment. Chapter 16. Voice AI and Phone Agent We build Alexa, a phone agent that makes and receives phone calls. Inbound, outbound, speed to lead. As soon as someone fills a form, it calls them. And the analytics dashboard is amazing. It's better than any voice AI SaaS could give you. I'll show you the whole build. Chapter 70, Typeform Clone and Webhooks. Right in the middle of all this, we build a typeform clone and replace what\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 9,\n        \"cited_text\": \"most you'd use make.com for. Webhooks and functions, custom endpoints, all inside OpenTlaw built-in minutes. Chapter 18, Multi-Agent Orchestration Two agent systems dispatching work to each other. Your OpenClaw agent assigns tasks to CloudCode agent. And CloudCode agent will assign tasks to OpenClaw agent. We see our application Superbase assign tasks. And these agents build it, ship it back, and OpenClaw will review it. If it's not right, it sends it back with nodes Fully autonomous And chapter 19 is agent-to-agent communication\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 10,\n        \"cited_text\": \"Discord as your AI team's Slack handle I'll show you how to set it up A server, I will meet my agent, set it up And these agents talk to each other They send alerts, request send updates and escalate when they need you. Every agent has its own bot, its own channel, its own presence. In chapter 20, I discuss how these agents can talk to each other. Agent communication. Instead of you going back and forth, agents asking is this okay, you let them sit in a council and discuss it among themselves. They debate, they decide, they come to you only when they need approval.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 11,\n        \"cited_text\": \"And chapter 21, Command Center Pipeline, an eight-phase autonomous pipeline that builds, deploys, and reports while you sleep. This is the full orchestration engine running 24-7. And chapter 22, Cronjobs and Automations, polling, webhooks, heartbeats, scheduled tasks, telegram notifications. We wire everything so your agents stay alive. And responsive around the clock. And finally, chapter 23. Claw Alley. I built a platform where AI agents transact with other AI agents in real time. Real crypto, real blockchain, real money from my wallet.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"source_id\": \"89e7dd43-0d39-4e38-8e5c-014fd5c75584\",\n        \"citation_number\": 12,\n        \"cited_text\": \"USDC on base network. I will show you a live transaction. One agent buying a service from another AI agent. and payment was confirmed on-chain. I believe this is the future of agent-to-agent commerce. And if you want the free guide that covers everything we discussed today, you can find that and link in the description below. Now, let's start building. So what is OpenClaw? OpenClaw is an open-source AI assistant platform that is one of the fastest-strong repos on GitHub. Help it has more than 265 000 stars at the time of this recording and all the\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n","name":"nlm notebook"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774984752476}}
