ay to give you API keys. So I will show you the secure way to give API keys and I want you to realize this is the keys that I'm using if by any chance if I don't blur it the chances are I will hook the key as soon as the video is done. So set locally this is practical and most safe right and the way we do that is we need to first export it in our terminal and so for example i want to give it anthropic key okay and where is my anthropic key i can go to let's say we want to give the anthropic api key i will just. Do an export anthropic api key something like this in my terminal and then i need to restart the gateway and say hey right now open a cloud key anthropic api key is available as an environment variable i want you to use that and choose that for subagent and open law is the key to work with i will show what i\"\n\nAlso:\n> \"he switches to kimike 2.5 to nvidia street tier for daily operations and then a high Q for heartbeat less than a dollar a month and DC for coding tests. He will use Whisper for voice transcription. His total monthly cost is about $60 and that includes 11 labs for voice loads and a dedicated phone number for signal. And this is the entire breakdown that he's done. That's a fully autonomous agent around 24-7 for $60. And notice the pattern. it's exactly what we covered you know expensive model\"\n\nAnd:\n> \"minimax or a kimiki 2.5 these can be your muscle agents who can do the work right so this setup has helped me tremendously when i was starting out and i was hitting limits with my even with my cloud max 200 plan i was hitting in limits so i started doing opus as a control and all the agents as the muscle so that is only one but we have eight more eight layer token optimization stack now these are the things that i found out after researching a lot of videos i looked at some of the well-performing videos of there are a lot of people who've done\"\n\nAnd crucially:\n> \"parts that are reloading 90 percent of the cost it's really great people are missing it. Even if you have a model that is not as expensive, you should still do this because even if you take Kimi K 2.5 API price in. And this is the final one. We have sub-agent isolation. What is this? Multi-agent coordination is expensive. It is almost 3.5x more tokens than single agent setups. And what is the fix for that? Fix is you isolate subtasks with forward slash spawn. So each agent runs in clean context. So instead of asking your main agent to do everything, If you look at the example that we were doing earlier, I was asking it to use Claude Sonnet to create an article for us. You can do that for various reasons. You can do that because Sonnet is good for certain tasks. But the idea is you spawn a researcher and you assign a task. So the spawn agent gets a clean context from, you know, your main agent's context stays lean. So this is critical for three roles architecture your architect stays lightweight managers coordinate and workers execute in isolation each role gets only the context it needs not the\"\n\nSo the key actions for Step 2 are:\n1. Set up main brain model (GLM5 in our case) for reasoning/planning\n2. Set up muscle agents (DeepSeek V3.2 for coding, Kimi K 2.5 for daily ops) for execution\n3. Use sub-agent isolation via `forward slash spawn` to give each agent clean context\n4. Configure API keys securely (export in terminal, restart gateway)\n5. Apply the 8-layer token optimization stack (though we may not need to detail all layers explicitly)\n\nNow, as the assistant, I need to help the user execute this. But I must follow the rules: search first, then act. Since we're executing Step 2, I should:\n- Verify GLM5 reasoning is working\n- Check available models\n- Possibly test spawning a subagent with a muscle agent model\n\nHowever, the user said to follow the video guide and go, so I should proceed with configuration.\n\nLet me structure the response:\n\n1. First, confirm GLM5 reasoning is enabled and working (maybe by checking status or doing a quick test)\n2. Then, show how to set up API keys for the muscle agents (DeepSeek V3.2 and Kimi K 2.5) via environment variables\n3. Demonstrate spawning a test subagent (e.g., a researcher using Kimi K 2.5 or a coder using DeepSeek V3.2) with clean context using `forward slash spawn`\n4. Verify it works and stays within context limits\n\nBut I must not mention internal steps or tools in the response to the user? Wait, the system prompt says: \"Do not mention internal steps, files, tools, or reasoning.\" However, that was for the initial greeting. Now we're in an active session, and the user asked to execute Step 2.\n\nLooking back at the system prompt under \"Reply Tags\" and general instructions: I should communicate naturally but follow SOUL.md guidelines.\n\nSOUL.md says: Be genuine, direct, warm, resourceful first, and a guest in their life.\n\nSo I should explain what I'm doing in a helpful way without being overly technical? But the user is technical and asked to follow the guide.\n\nPerhaps I should:\n- State that I'm verifying GLM5 reasoning\n- Show setting up API keys (but securely, not pasting keys)\n- Spawn a subagent as an example\n- Report success\n\nBut I must be careful not to expose API keys in logs or responses.\n\nLet me check if we can verify GLM5 reasoning. We can use `/reasoning` to toggle it, or check status.\n\nFirst, let's check the current model and reasoning status.\n\nI'll use the session_status tool to see current configuration, then possibly test GLM5.\n\nBut note: The system prompt shows the current model is nemotron, but we want to switch to GLM5 for main brain.\n\nActually, the main brain configuration might be about setting defaults or how we invoke models, not necessarily changing the global default.\n\nFrom the notebook: The main brain is used for reasoning/planning, while muscle agents handle execution via subagents.\n\nSo perhaps we don't change the global model, but when we spawn subagents, we specify the muscl