easoning, but we can also check if reasoning is enabled by trying to toggle it? However, we don't have a direct tool for that. We can just use GLM5 and see if it performs well.\n\nAlternatively, we can run a quick test by asking the main agent (which is GLM5) a reasoning question and see if it responds appropriately.\n\nBut note: The main agent is currently GLM5 (as per the system prompt when we started). We can use that.\n\nStep 2: Spawn a subagent for research using Kimi K 2.5.\n\nWe have the notebooklm skill and youtube-research skill. We can test spawning a subagent that uses Kimi K 2.5 to do a quick research task.\n\nHowever, we need to know how to specify the model for a subagent. From the notebook, we saw that we can set the model per agent in the configuration. But we don't have the exact configuration file.\n\nAlternatively, when we spawn a subagent, we can specify the model via the `model` parameter in `sessions_spawn`.\n\nLet's try:\n\nWe'll spawn a subagent with the task: \"List the available skills in the workspace and report back which ones are research-related.\" (We did this earlier with the researcher subagent, but that time we didn't specify a model and it used the default? Actually, we used the researcher agent which has a subagents.model set to anthropic/claude-sonnet-4 in the config, but that didn't work because we don't have that model. So we got a fallback.)\n\nThis time, we want to specify the model explicitly.\n\nLet's spawn a subagent with model set to \"nvidia/moonshotai/kimi-k2.5\" (which is the alias for kimi) or \"nvidia/deepseek-ai/deepseek-v3.2\".\n\nWe'll do two tests: one for research (using Kimi) and one for coding (using DeepSeek).\n\nBut first, let's check if we can spawn a subagent with a specific model.\n\nWe'll use the `sessions_spawn` tool with the `model` parameter.\n\nLet's start with a research task using Kimi K 2.5.\n\nWe'll also need to wait for the subagent to complete. We can either wait for the auto-announcement or use `sessions_yield` after spawning? But note: The user said to reply after we finished everything, so we can spawn the subagent and then wait for it to finish (by not replying until we get the completion event).\n\nHowever, we are in a conversation and we need to reply to the user eventually. We can spawn the subagent and then wait for the completion event (which will come as a message) and then we can reply.\n\nBut note: The user said \"if you have work reply after you finished everything.\" So we should not reply until the subagent task is done.\n\nLet's do:\n\n1. Spawn a subagent for research using Kimi K 2.5.\n2. Wait for the completion event (we'll get a message from the subagent when it's done).\n3. Then, we can reply to the user with the result.\n\nBut note: We are in the middle of a conversation and we have to follow the user's instruction to reply after we finish everything.\n\nWe'll do the same for a coding task if needed, but let's start with one.\n\nLet's spawn the subagent.\n\nWe'll use:\n- runtime: subagent\n- agentId: we don't have a specific agentId for kimi, but we can use the generic subagent runtime and specify the model.\n- task: \"List the available skills in the workspace and report back which ones are research-related.\"\n- model: \"nvidia/moonshotai/kimi-k2.5\" (the kimi model)\n\nBut note: The `sessions_spawn` tool does not have a `model` parameter? Wait, looking back at the tool description for `sessions_spawn`, I see it does have a `model` parameter.\n\nYes, in the `sessions_spawn` tool, there is a `model` parameter.\n\nLet's use it.\n\nWe'll also set the label to something like \"researcher-kimi\".\n\nLet's do it.\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_85e250445ab1426c99d07dad","name":"sessions_spawn","arguments":{"task":"List the available skills in the workspace and report back which ones are research-related.","label":"researcher-kimi","model":"nvidia/moonshotai/kimi-k2.5","runtime":"subagent"}}],"ap